## OpenAPI Specification

### Why Use OpenAPI

- **Machine-readable**: Enables tooling and automation
- **Single source of truth**: API and docs stay in sync
- **Code generation**: Generate clients and servers
- **Testing**: Automated API testing
- **Interactive docs**: Auto-generated interactive documentation

### OpenAPI Structure

```yaml
openapi: 3.0.0
info:
  title: API Name
  version: 1.0.0
  description: API description
  contact:
    name: API Support
    email: support@example.com
  license:
    name: MIT
servers:
  - url: https://api.example.com/v1
    description: Production server
  - url: https://staging-api.example.com/v1
    description: Staging server
paths:
  /users:
    get:
      summary: List users
      operationId: listUsers
      tags:
        - Users
      parameters:
        - name: limit
          in: query
          schema:
            type: integer
            default: 20
      responses:
        '200':
          description: Successful response
components:
  securitySchemes:
    bearerAuth:
      type: http
      scheme: bearer
      bearerFormat: JWT
  schemas:
    User:
      type: object
      required:
        - id
        - name
        - email
      properties:
        id:
          type: integer
        name:
          type: string
        email:
          type: string
          format: email
```

### OpenAPI Best Practices

- **Version your spec**: Include version in info section
- **Use schemas**: Define reusable data models
- **Document all endpoints**: Include all available endpoints
- **Add examples**: Include request/response examples
- **Use tags**: Organize endpoints logically
- **Security schemes**: Document authentication methods

